\title{Molfeat}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{"Molecular featurization for ML (100+ featurizers). ECFP, MACCS, descriptors, pretrained models (ChemBERTa), convert SMILES to features, for QSAR and molecular ML."}

\subtree{
\title{Molfeat - Molecular Featurization Hub}
\subtree{
\title{Overview}
\p{Molfeat is a comprehensive Python library for molecular featurization that unifies 100+ pre-trained embeddings and hand-crafted featurizers. Convert chemical structures (SMILES strings or RDKit molecules) into numerical representations for machine learning tasks including QSAR modeling, virtual screening, similarity searching, and deep learning applications. Features fast parallel processing, scikit-learn compatible transformers, and built-in caching.}
}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use This Skill}
\p{This skill should be used when working with:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Molecular machine learning}: Building QSAR/QSPR models, property prediction}
\li{\strong{Virtual screening}: Ranking compound libraries for biological activity}
\li{\strong{Similarity searching}: Finding structurally similar molecules}
\li{\strong{Chemical space analysis}: Clustering, visualization, dimensionality reduction}
\li{\strong{Deep learning}: Training neural networks on molecular data}
\li{\strong{Featurization pipelines}: Converting SMILES to ML-ready representations}
\li{\strong{Cheminformatics}: Any task requiring molecular feature extraction}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Installation}
\pre{\startverb
uv pip install molfeat

# With all optional dependencies
uv pip install "molfeat[all]"
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Optional dependencies for specific featurizers:}}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb molfeat[dgl]\stopverb} - GNN models (GIN variants)}
\li{\code{\startverb molfeat[graphormer]\stopverb} - Graphormer models}
\li{\code{\startverb molfeat[transformer]\stopverb} - ChemBERTa, ChemGPT, MolT5}
\li{\code{\startverb molfeat[fcd]\stopverb} - FCD descriptors}
\li{\code{\startverb molfeat[map4]\stopverb} - MAP4 fingerprints}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Core Concepts}
\p{Molfeat organizes featurization into three hierarchical classes:}

\subtree{
\title{1. Calculators (\code{\startverb molfeat.calc\stopverb})}
\p{Callable objects that convert individual molecules into feature vectors. Accept RDKit \code{\startverb Chem.Mol\stopverb} objects or SMILES strings.}

\p{\strong{Use calculators for:}}

\ul{
\li{Single molecule featurization}
\li{Custom processing loops}
\li{Direct feature computation}
}

\p{\strong{Example:}}

\pre{\startverb
from molfeat.calc import FPCalculator

calc = FPCalculator("ecfp", radius=3, fpSize=2048)
features = calc("CCO")  # Returns numpy array (2048,)
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{2. Transformers (\code{\startverb molfeat.trans\stopverb})}
\p{Scikit-learn compatible transformers that wrap calculators for batch processing with parallelization.}

\p{\strong{Use transformers for:}}

\ul{
\li{Batch featurization of molecular datasets}
\li{Integration with scikit-learn pipelines}
\li{Parallel processing (automatic CPU utilization)}
}

\p{\strong{Example:}}

\pre{\startverb
from molfeat.trans import MoleculeTransformer
from molfeat.calc import FPCalculator

transformer = MoleculeTransformer(FPCalculator("ecfp"), n_jobs=-1)
features = transformer(smiles_list)  # Parallel processing
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{3. Pretrained Transformers (\code{\startverb molfeat.trans.pretrained\stopverb})}
\p{Specialized transformers for deep learning models with batched inference and caching.}

\p{\strong{Use pretrained transformers for:}}

\ul{
\li{State-of-the-art molecular embeddings}
\li{Transfer learning from large chemical datasets}
\li{Deep learning feature extraction}
}

\p{\strong{Example:}}

\pre{\startverb
from molfeat.trans.pretrained import PretrainedMolTransformer

transformer = PretrainedMolTransformer("ChemBERTa-77M-MLM", n_jobs=-1)
embeddings = transformer(smiles_list)  # Deep learning embeddings
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Quick Start Workflow}
\subtree{
\title{Basic Featurization}
\pre{\startverb
import datamol as dm
from molfeat.calc import FPCalculator
from molfeat.trans import MoleculeTransformer

# Load molecular data
smiles = ["CCO", "CC(=O)O", "c1ccccc1", "CC(C)O"]

# Create calculator and transformer
calc = FPCalculator("ecfp", radius=3)
transformer = MoleculeTransformer(calc, n_jobs=-1)

# Featurize molecules
features = transformer(smiles)
print(f"Shape: {features.shape}")  # (4, 2048)
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Save and Load Configuration}
\pre{\startverb
# Save featurizer configuration for reproducibility
transformer.to_state_yaml_file("featurizer_config.yml")

# Reload exact configuration
loaded = MoleculeTransformer.from_state_yaml_file("featurizer_config.yml")
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Handle Errors Gracefully}
\pre{\startverb
# Process dataset with potentially invalid SMILES
transformer = MoleculeTransformer(
    calc,
    n_jobs=-1,
    ignore_errors=True,  # Continue on failures
    verbose=True          # Log error details
)

features = transformer(smiles_with_errors)
# Returns None for failed molecules
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Choosing the Right Featurizer}
\subtree{
\title{For Traditional Machine Learning (RF, SVM, XGBoost)}
\p{\strong{Start with fingerprints:}}

\pre{\startverb
# ECFP - Most popular, general-purpose
FPCalculator("ecfp", radius=3, fpSize=2048)

# MACCS - Fast, good for scaffold hopping
FPCalculator("maccs")

# MAP4 - Efficient for large-scale screening
FPCalculator("map4")
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{For interpretable models:}}

\pre{\startverb
# RDKit 2D descriptors (200+ named properties)
from molfeat.calc import RDKitDescriptors2D
RDKitDescriptors2D()

# Mordred (1800+ comprehensive descriptors)
from molfeat.calc import MordredDescriptors
MordredDescriptors()
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Combine multiple featurizers:}}

\pre{\startverb
from molfeat.trans import FeatConcat

concat = FeatConcat([
    FPCalculator("maccs"),      # 167 dimensions
    FPCalculator("ecfp")         # 2048 dimensions
])  # Result: 2215-dimensional combined features
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{For Deep Learning}
\p{\strong{Transformer-based embeddings:}}

\pre{\startverb
# ChemBERTa - Pre-trained on 77M PubChem compounds
PretrainedMolTransformer("ChemBERTa-77M-MLM")

# ChemGPT - Autoregressive language model
PretrainedMolTransformer("ChemGPT-1.2B")
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Graph neural networks:}}

\pre{\startverb
# GIN models with different pre-training objectives
PretrainedMolTransformer("gin-supervised-masking")
PretrainedMolTransformer("gin-supervised-infomax")

# Graphormer for quantum chemistry
PretrainedMolTransformer("Graphormer-pcqm4mv2")
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{For Similarity Searching}
\pre{\startverb
# ECFP - General purpose, most widely used
FPCalculator("ecfp")

# MACCS - Fast, scaffold-based similarity
FPCalculator("maccs")

# MAP4 - Efficient for large databases
FPCalculator("map4")

# USR/USRCAT - 3D shape similarity
from molfeat.calc import USRDescriptors
USRDescriptors()
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{For Pharmacophore-Based Approaches}
\pre{\startverb
# FCFP - Functional group based
FPCalculator("fcfp")

# CATS - Pharmacophore pair distributions
from molfeat.calc import CATSCalculator
CATSCalculator(mode="2D")

# Gobbi - Explicit pharmacophore features
FPCalculator("gobbi2D")
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Common Workflows}
\subtree{
\title{Building a QSAR Model}
\pre{\startverb
from molfeat.trans import MoleculeTransformer
from molfeat.calc import FPCalculator
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score

# Featurize molecules
transformer = MoleculeTransformer(FPCalculator("ecfp"), n_jobs=-1)
X = transformer(smiles_train)

# Train model
model = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100)
scores = cross_val_score(model, X, y_train, cv=5)
print(f"R² = {scores.mean():.3f}")

# Save configuration for deployment
transformer.to_state_yaml_file("production_featurizer.yml")
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Virtual Screening Pipeline}
\pre{\startverb
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier

# Train on known actives/inactives
transformer = MoleculeTransformer(FPCalculator("ecfp"), n_jobs=-1)
X_train = transformer(train_smiles)
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=500)
clf.fit(X_train, train_labels)

# Screen large library
X_screen = transformer(screening_library)  # e.g., 1M compounds
predictions = clf.predict_proba(X_screen)[:, 1]

# Rank and select top hits
top_indices = predictions.argsort()[::-1][:1000]
top_hits = [screening_library[i] for i in top_indices]
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Similarity Search}
\pre{\startverb
from sklearn.metrics.pairwise import cosine_similarity

# Query molecule
calc = FPCalculator("ecfp")
query_fp = calc(query_smiles).reshape(1, -1)

# Database fingerprints
transformer = MoleculeTransformer(calc, n_jobs=-1)
database_fps = transformer(database_smiles)

# Compute similarity
similarities = cosine_similarity(query_fp, database_fps)[0]
top_similar = similarities.argsort()[-10:][::-1]
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Scikit-learn Pipeline Integration}
\pre{\startverb
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier

# Create end-to-end pipeline
pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('featurizer', MoleculeTransformer(FPCalculator("ecfp"), n_jobs=-1)),
    ('classifier', RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100))
])

# Train and predict directly on SMILES
pipeline.fit(smiles_train, y_train)
predictions = pipeline.predict(smiles_test)
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Comparing Multiple Featurizers}
\pre{\startverb
featurizers = {
    'ECFP': FPCalculator("ecfp"),
    'MACCS': FPCalculator("maccs"),
    'Descriptors': RDKitDescriptors2D(),
    'ChemBERTa': PretrainedMolTransformer("ChemBERTa-77M-MLM")
}

results = {}
for name, feat in featurizers.items():
    transformer = MoleculeTransformer(feat, n_jobs=-1)
    X = transformer(smiles)
    # Evaluate with your ML model
    score = evaluate_model(X, y)
    results[name] = score
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Discovering Available Featurizers}
\p{Use the ModelStore to explore all available featurizers:}

\pre{\startverb
from molfeat.store.modelstore import ModelStore

store = ModelStore()

# List all available models
all_models = store.available_models
print(f"Total featurizers: {len(all_models)}")

# Search for specific models
chemberta_models = store.search(name="ChemBERTa")
for model in chemberta_models:
    print(f"- {model.name}: {model.description}")

# Get usage information
model_card = store.search(name="ChemBERTa-77M-MLM")[0]
model_card.usage()  # Display usage examples

# Load model
transformer = store.load("ChemBERTa-77M-MLM")
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Advanced Features}
\subtree{
\title{Custom Preprocessing}
\pre{\startverb
class CustomTransformer(MoleculeTransformer):
    def preprocess(self, mol):
        """Custom preprocessing pipeline"""
        if isinstance(mol, str):
            mol = dm.to_mol(mol)
        mol = dm.standardize_mol(mol)
        mol = dm.remove_salts(mol)
        return mol

transformer = CustomTransformer(FPCalculator("ecfp"), n_jobs=-1)
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Batch Processing Large Datasets}
\pre{\startverb
def featurize_in_chunks(smiles_list, transformer, chunk_size=10000):
    """Process large datasets in chunks to manage memory"""
    all_features = []
    for i in range(0, len(smiles_list), chunk_size):
        chunk = smiles_list[i:i+chunk_size]
        features = transformer(chunk)
        all_features.append(features)
    return np.vstack(all_features)
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Caching Expensive Embeddings}
\pre{\startverb
import pickle

cache_file = "embeddings_cache.pkl"
transformer = PretrainedMolTransformer("ChemBERTa-77M-MLM", n_jobs=-1)

try:
    with open(cache_file, "rb") as f:
        embeddings = pickle.load(f)
except FileNotFoundError:
    embeddings = transformer(smiles_list)
    with open(cache_file, "wb") as f:
        pickle.dump(embeddings, f)
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Performance Tips}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Use parallelization}: Set \code{\startverb n_jobs=-1\stopverb} to utilize all CPU cores}
\li{\strong{Batch processing}: Process multiple molecules at once instead of loops}
\li{\strong{Choose appropriate featurizers}: Fingerprints are faster than deep learning models}
\li{\strong{Cache pretrained models}: Leverage built-in caching for repeated use}
\li{\strong{Use float32}: Set \code{\startverb dtype=np.float32\stopverb} when precision allows}
\li{\strong{Handle errors efficiently}: Use \code{\startverb ignore_errors=True\stopverb} for large datasets}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Common Featurizers Reference}
\p{\strong{Quick reference for frequently used featurizers:}}

\pre{\startverb
| Featurizer | Type | Dimensions | Speed | Use Case |
|------------|------|------------|-------|----------|
| `ecfp` | Fingerprint | 2048 | Fast | General purpose |
| `maccs` | Fingerprint | 167 | Very fast | Scaffold similarity |
| `desc2D` | Descriptors | 200+ | Fast | Interpretable models |
| `mordred` | Descriptors | 1800+ | Medium | Comprehensive features |
| `map4` | Fingerprint | 1024 | Fast | Large-scale screening |
| `ChemBERTa-77M-MLM` | Deep learning | 768 | Slow* | Transfer learning |
| `gin-supervised-masking` | GNN | Variable | Slow* | Graph-based models |
\stopverb}

\p{*First run is slow; subsequent runs benefit from caching}
}

